caption.paragraph:
FIGURE 2.
Waldeckia australiensis
(Haswell, 1879b), head and urosome; (a) female, AM P.71810, (b) male, AM P.71808, (c) male, AM P.71809, all from off Wattamolla, New South Wales; (d) male, AM P.71780, from Taupo Seamount, Tasman Sea.

FIGURE 3.
Waldeckia australiensis
(Haswell, 1879b), all parts from female, AM P.71811, except male a, A1, 2, AM P.71809, and male b, A2, AM P.71808; all from off Wattamolla, New South Wales, Australia. Scale bars: 0.2 mm.

FIGURE 5.
Waldeckia australiensis
(Haswell, 1879b), all parts from female, AM P.71811, except ♂ G2 palm, from male, AM P.71809; both from off Wattamolla, New South Wales, Australia. Scale bars: 0.2 mm.

subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnostic description. Head lateral cephalic lobe large, narrowly rounded in female, subacute and occasionally down-turned in male. Antenna 1 peduncular article 1 without anterodistal projection. Labrum, epistome and upper lip fused. Mandible palp article 2 anterodistal margin setose; article 3 with marginal and apical setae. Labium without apical stylets on each lobe.
Gnathopod 1
parachelate; basis anterior margin with slender setae; propodus posterior margin smooth to weakly crenate .
Gnathopod 2 slightly to strongly chelate
; carpus long; propodus palm slightly to strongly obtuse, straight; dactylus fitting palm . Pereopod 6 basis posteroventral margin rounded.
Pereopod 7 basis
, posterior margin almost straight, minutely crenate, posteroventral margin oblique (slightly concave) . Epimeron 3 posteroventral corner subquadrate/narrowly rounded. Urosomite 1 dorsally smooth.
Uropod 1 outer ramus slightly longer than inner ramus
; uropod 2 rami subequal in length; uropod 3 rami subequal in length, inner ramus reaching article 2 of outer ramus.

Remarks. This is a common species in Australian waters and exhibits some morphological variability, particularly in the form of the lateral cephalic lobes, which in the male can be variously down-ward pointing, but also in the gnathopod 2 which can be slightly to strongly chelate, but with the dactylus always fitting the palm.

Ren’s ( 2012 ) record of
Waldeckia australiensis
from the South China Sea, although very similar to that species, differs in having apical stylets on the outer lobes of the labium.
Distribution. Australia : South Australia ; Tasmania; Victoria; New South Wales ; Queensland (Great Barrier Reef); and Taupo and Derwent Hunter Seamounts, Tasman Sea.
